The police arrested three cadres of Chand-led outfit following the incident. No casualties were reported. Police also seized huge cache of improvised explosive devices from the cadres.

On 3 May 2020, leaders and cadres of Nepali Congress protested in front of the Narayani Hospital in Birgunj City (Parsa district). The protesters were demanding that the government make the Narayani Hospital into a general hospital and provide all services and treatments in the hospital. Recently, the government had made Narayani hospital into a coronavirus hospital, and the treatments for all other diseases had been halted in the hospital. [size=no report]

Around 3 May 2020 (as reported), a clash ensued between the locals and ward representatives in Mujeliya ward of Janakpur Sub-metropolitan city (Dhanusha district), after the locals accused the ward chairman of discriminating in creating the name list for relief distribution. The government has been trying to prepare a list to distribute relief packages to the people affected by coronavirus related lockdown. [size=no report]

On 3 May 2020, police intervened the locals, who were protesting by obstructing relief distribution in Paterwasugauli Rural Municipality-5 near Supauli area (Parsa district). The locals accused the authorities of discrimination in the distribution of coronavirus related relief packages. Police arrested 10 people for creating obstruction in the distribution process. [size=at least 10]

On 3 May 2020, more than 200 women picketed the Mahakali Municipal Office in Mahakali locality (Kanchanpur district). The protesters demanded that the mayor make arrangements to bring back their families, who were stranded in India due to coronavirus related lockdown. [size=more than 200]

On 3 May 2020, locals protested by staging a protest rally in Masuriya locality (Kailali district), demanding investigation into the alleged murder of the central vice-chairman of the National Private and Boarding Schools Association Nepal. [size=no report]

On 2 May 2020, locals of Adarshanagar locality staged a protest in Birgunj City (Parsa district). The protesters were demanding that the government make the Narayani Hospital into a general hospital and provide all services and treatments in the hospital. Recently, the government had made Narayani hospital into a coronavirus hospital, and the treatments for all other diseases had been halted in the hospital. [size=no report]

On 30 April 2020, an unidentified group detonated a bomb in Duwagaun village of Triveni Rural Municipality-7 near Holeri area (Rolpa district). Four persons were killed in the incident. Further investigation is ongoing.

Around 29 April 2020, locals protested by padlocking the ward office of Kanchanrup Municipality-9 (Saptari district). The protesters were accusing the authorities of distributing relief materials to the well-to-do families instead of daily wageworkers and poor families, who were affected by coronavirus related lockdown. [size=no report]

On 28 April 2020, a clash ensued between demonstrators belonging to Nepal Tarun Dal and the police in Damauli locality (Tanahun district), while the former were demonstrating against recent activities of the government including alleged corruption in procurement of medical equipment to combat the coronavirus epidemic. [size=no report]

Around 27 April 2020, Indian nationals assaulted two police officers stationed at Nepal-India border in Semari locality of Yashodhara Rural Municipality-7 near Kapilvastu area (Kapilbastu district). The incident occurred as a retaliation to an assault of an Indian villager, who had crossed the border while grazing his cattle, by Nepali officers. [size=no report]

Around 27 April 2020, Nepal police stationed at the Nepal-India border in Semari locality of Yashodhara Rural Municipality-7 assaulted an Indian farmer near Kapilvastu area (Kapilbastu district). The incident occurred when the Indian villager crossed the Nepal-India border while grazing his cattle. The police have been enforcing strict border lockdown as a preventative measure to minimize the spread of coronavirus.

On 25 April 2020, locals demonstrated by staging a whistle rally in Adarshanagar locality of Birgunj city (Parsa district), demanding the authorities to resume the treatment of diseases, other than coronavirus, in the Narayani hospital. The government had declared the hospital as coronavirus hospital and halted the treatment of all other diseases in the facility. [size=no report]

On 25 April 2020, students associated with Socialist Party [Samajbadi party] protested by maintaining social distancing in Ghantaghar Chok of Birgunj city (Parsa district). The students were demanding the government to make arrangements for bringing back Nepali students, who were stuck abroad due to coronavirus related lockdown. [size=no report]

On May 17, a group of rioters, including a member of the parliament, torched a toll booth in Tikauli locality (Chitwan district, Narayani). The demonstrators were expressing dissatisfaction with the tax levied by the Road Board in the area. A police officer sustained burn while trying to prevent the rioters from torching the area. [size=no report]

On May 16, Nepal police fired shots at Indian rioters, who were trying to rescue an Indian national arrested within the Nepal border with a pistol and a magazine, in Siddharthanagar Municipality (Rupandehi district, Lumbini). One person died from the gunshot wound [size=15-20]

On May 16, journalists, including members of the Nepal Press Union- Kaski chapter, staged a protest rally in BP chowk of Pokhara city (Kaski district, Gandaki). The protesters were expressing dissatisfaction over the recently tabled Media Council Bill, which they claimed were against press freedom. [size=no report]

actor2: Police Forces of Nepal (2015-) Armed Police Force
notes: On May 16, Nepal Police and Armed Police Force intervened a protest rally organized by the journalists, including members of the Nepal Press Union, in front of the District Administration Office premises in Phidim city (Panchthar district, Mechi). The protesters were expressing dissatisfaction over the recently tabled Media Council Bill, which they claimed were against press freedom. [size=no report]

On May 16, students demonstrated by vandalizing Dadeldhura Multiple Campus in Amargadhi city (Dadeldhura district, Mahakali). The demonstrators were expressing dissatisfaction over the recruitment of three new individuals, which they claimed was politically motivated, and based on quid pro quo. [size=no report]

On May 16, local residents continued their demonstrations by obstructing vehicular movement using barricades in Chapagaun-Saddobato road section in Chapagaun city (Lalitpur district, Bagmati). The demonstrators were expressing dissatisfaction over the delay in road construction, which had resulted in dust pollution, along with muddied streets, in the area. [size=no report]

assoc_actor_1: FNJ: Federation of Nepali Journalists; Journalists (Nepal)
notes: On May 15, Kaski-based journalists, along with the members of the Federation of Nepali Journalists, organized a protest program in Pokhara city (Kaski district, Gandaki), to object the Media Council Bill tabled in the parliament by the government. [size=no report]

assoc_actor_1: NPU: Nepal Press Union; FNJ: Federation of Nepali Journalists; Journalists (Nepal)
notes: On May 15, journalists, including members of the Nepal Press Union and the Federation of Nepali Journalists, protested in Itahari chowk (Sunsari district, Koshi). The protesters were expressing dissatisfaction over the Media Council Bill, recently tabled in the parliament, which they claimed violated press freedom. [size=no report]

On May 15, elected representatives, including a mayor, a provincial assembly member and a member of the House of Representatives, protested against the Pashupati Area Development Trust's plan to close the Tilganga-Tamaraganga road section in Pashupati area of Kathmandu city (Kathmandu district, Bagmati). [size=about 50]

On May 15, locals protested by obstructing the construction of 200kV substation by the banks of the Trishuli River in Paharbesi locality near Bidur area (Nuwakot district, Bagmati). The locals were dissatisfied with the location of the wall built around the command center of the substation, and were demanding for its location to be shifted. [size=no report]

On May 15, local residents took to streets and staged demonstrations by obstructing vehicular movement using barricades in Chapagaun-Saddobato road section in Chapagaun city (Lalitpur district, Bagmati). The demonstrators were expressing dissatisfaction over the delay in road construction, which had resulted in dust pollution, along with muddied streets, in the area. [size=no report]

On May 14, locals protested by obstructing the Lahan Municipality cleaners from dumping trash in the Waste Management Center located in their community in Lahan city (Siraha district, Sagarmatha). The protesters were dissatisfied with the smell emitted from the trash dumped in their locality, which they claimed resulted in health related problems, including headache, nausea, and breathing difficulties. [size=no report]

On May 14, locals protested by chanting slogans in front of the office of Department of Roads in Patan city (Lalitpur district, Bagmati). The protesters were expressing dissatisfaction over the delay in Chapagaun-Saddobato road construction, which had resulted in severe air pollution, along with muddied streets, in the area. [size=no report]

On May 13, the main opposition party, Nepali Congress, protested by obstructing the provincial assembly session of Province 3 in Hetauda city (Makwanpur district), demanding that the permanent capital of the province be decided without further delay. [size=no report]

Afterwards a clash ensued where locals from both sides hurled stones at each other. Dev Narayan Yadav, the former chairman of District Development Committee, among others, sustained serious head injuries in the incident.

Private medical college proprietors organised a protest demonstration in Kathmandu calling for the scrapping of the agreement reached with Dr Govinda KC. They assembled at Maitighar Mandala and held a protest rally from there up to Naya Baneshwar. They asserted that the agreement that the government has reached with Dr KC would jeopardise private medical colleges.

Transport, schools and industries in Tanahun were affected Monday due to a strike called by a splinter Maoist group, led by Netra Bikram Chand. The group, a breakaway faction of the Unified Maoist party, was demonstrating police action against slum-dwellers in southern Nepal's Sarlahi district. The group said police had used force to evict people living in a slum last month. Six cadres of the party were arrested in Tanahun headquarters, Damauli, for enforcing the strike.

Transport, schools and industries in Sarlahi were affected Monday due to a strike called by a splinter Maoist group, led by Netra Bikram Chand. The group, a breakaway faction of the Unified Maoist party, was demonstrating police action against slum-dwellers in southern Nepal's Sarlahi district. The group said police had used force to evict people living in a slum last month. In Sarlahi, police arrested a CPN Maoist cadre while they were trying to hurl a petrol bomb at a loaded truck.

Transport, schools and industries in the capital were forced shut Monday due to a strike called by a splinter Maoist group, led by Netra Bikram Chand. The group, a breakaway faction of the Unified Maoist party, was demonstrating police action against slum-dwellers in southern Nepal's Sarlahi district. The group said police had used force to evict people living in a slum last month. More than 80 party members were arrested in Kathmandu on Monday for trying to enforce the strike. Two taxis, in Gongabu and Baneshwor, were completely damaged when they were torched by banda enforcers.

6-10 supporters of Dr Govinda KC were injured when police charged with batons in Tangal, Kathmandu on Sunday morning. Doctors, nurses, medical students, social activists, and the general public gathered in front of the headquarters of the Commission for the Investigation of Abuse of Authority (CIAA) to protest against CIAA chief Lokman Singh Karki, who's impeachment was being demanded by Govinda. Four of the protesters had to be admitted to hospital for their injuries.

Nepal Student Union cadres launched a relay hunger strike, demanding that its mother party, the Nepali Congress, hold their 11th national general convention on time. As many as 11 NSC leaders, including Kundan Kafle, a prospective candidate for the student union's president, participated in the protest launched in front of the NC party office in Sanepa, Patan.

Supporters of Dr Govinda KC held a mass rally in Kathmandu on Saturday to express their support for the fasting doctor and to pressure authorities to accept his demands. The rally, held around Maitighar-New Baneshwor, saw huge participation of youths, and was organized by the Bibeksheel Nepali political party. The participants played national songs, carried national flag, placards and pamphlets.

Bikram Bahadur Shahi, the headmaster of Nepal Rastriya Secondary School in Murma, and a group of men attacked DEO Jawaharlal Hamal and vandalised his office on Friday night. Hamal was attacked after he switched the bank account of Nepal Rastriya Secondary School following complaints of irregularities. This is the third time Hamal was assaulted. On February 16, supporters of the Mohan Baidya-led CPN-Maoist had attacked him for cancelling the teachers' quota programme for Yuba Barsha Primary School in Sorukot. Shahi was arrested two days later for the assault.

A large group of youths gathered at New Baneshwor, Kathmandu for a symbolic protest to draw the attention of Members of Parliament towards TUTH senior orthopedic surgeon Dr Govinda KC's indefinite hunger strike. They urged the government to accept the demands of Govinda in light of his deteriorating health.

A rally was held in Dhangadi in support of Dr Govinda KC, who had been staging a fast-unto-death for the past eleven days at TU Teaching Hospital, Maharajgunj, Kathmandu. People from different walks of life, including professors, representatives of FNCCI, party leaders, and medical doctors participated in the rally, demanding that the government accept the demands of Govinda.

Riot police today intervened in a protest rally organised by medical and dental health professionals in support of Dr Govinda KC after the latter allegedly tried to break through the barbed wire fence set up at the prohibited zone outside the Prime Minister's official residence in Baluwatar, Kathmandu. The demonstrating doctors called on the government to fulfil the demands put forth by Dr KC, and condemned both government apathy and the counter-demonstration against Dr Govinda. No injuries were reported on either side.

Scores of youth on Monday took the street of Narayangadh, Bharatpur in the support of Dr Govinda KC, an orthopedic surgeon who has been staging a fast-onto-death in Kathmandu for the last nine days. They protesters claimed that the government was ignoring the hunger strike.

Police arrested seven CPN (Maoist) cadres who were protesting and organizing a transport strike in Narayangadh, Bharatpur. The demonstrators cited the reason for the protest as government suppression of landless squatters in Sarlahi district.

CPN (Maoist) protesters demonstrated and attempted to organize a transport strike in Madi, Chitwan district (coded at Devendrapur locality, Madi, Chitawan). The demonstrators cited the reason for the protest as government suppression of landless squatters in Sarlahi district. One of the protesters was arrested by police.

A day after hundreds of people marched through the streets in the Capital in support of Dr Govinda KC, who has been on hunger strike, another group of protesters, including doctors and nurses led by the umbrella organisation of private medical and dental colleges, took to the streets on Sunday in opposition of some of his demands and of the hunger strike in general.

Around 200 demonstrators representing different unions, civil society leaders, and human rights activists took to the streets in support of Dr Govinda KC. Senor orthopedic surgeon Dr KC at Tribhuvan University Teaching Hospital had been staging a fast-unto-death hunger strike demanding reforms in medical education sector and the impeachment of CIAA Chief Lokman Singh Karki for the last six days.

In Kathmandu, Nepalese youths gathered in support of Prime Minister KP Oli and against the decision made by the CPN (Maoist-Centre) to withdraw support for the government. The Nepalese government on Friday decided to face a no-confidence motion at the parliament, filed by two major parties, the Nepali Congress and the CPN (Maoist-Centre).

On Tuesday, eight police personnel were injured as they clashed with landless squatters in Sarlahi district. The clash ensued after police tried to demolish huts constructed illegally encroaching the land of Sagarnath Forest Development Project.

The Sanghiya Gathabandhan, an alliance formed by the protesting Madhesi and Janajati forces, has started a protest and relay hunger strike in Rajbiraj, the district headquarters of Saptari. The fast began on Saturday.

A brawl broke out among the students of Nepali Congress (NC) aligned Nepal Students Union (NSU) during a programme chaired by senior NC leader Ram Chandra Poudel in Kathmandu on Wednesday. A student was injured in the fighting over addressing the programme.
Temporary school teachers across Mahottari on Monday staged sit-in in front of Jaleshwar-based District Education Office (DEO), demanding amendment to the recently revised Education Act.

On Sunday, Doctors organized a protest rally under the banner of Nepal Medical Association (NMA) in Birgunj, threatening to continue the shutdown of OPD services until the detained doctors are released.

Political groups led by Mohan Baidya and Netra Bikram Chand have demonstrated in the capital on Friday, one day after the unification of the UCPN (Maoist) with the nine fringe communist parties outside the Legislature-Parliamen.

notes: Students affiliated to All Nepal National Independent Students Union-Revolutionary today staged a sit-in protest in front of the Nepal Oil Corporation demanding smooth supply of petroleum products and action against black-marketeers.
On 3 Feb, UDMF agitators and importers clashed at Miteri bridge, when the importers had tried to bring in their consignments from across the border by removing the blockade put up by the agitators.

Agitating United Democratic Madhesi Front tried to block Nepali Congress central leader Bimalendra Nidhi from visiting his constituency on Wednesday in southern part of Janakpur Sub-Metropolitan City in Dhanusha district. After the police obstruction, they decided to stage a sit-in at local Shyam Chok. Police also engaged in a clash with demonstrators while dispersing them.

Agitating Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha (UDMF) activists staged demonstrations in various places in Janakpur since early morning. There was a heavy presence of the security personnel in the area to avert a possible clash between the NC supporters and the Morcha activists.

United Democratic Madhesi Front cadres were trying to foil the municipal convention of Nepali Congress in Rajbiraj, Saptari today. They were chanting slogans in front of the Nepali Congress election booth. Around one-and-a-half dozen UDMF were arrested. After the arrests, activists of the front staged demonstrations at various places demanding their release.
UDMF activists on Tuesday manhandled an NC polling officer tasked to hold the party convention in Golbazaar Municipality, Siraha.

Cadres of the United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF) on Monday vandalised the house of Nepali Congress central leader Bimalendra Nidhi and torched two motorcycles. Security personnel deployed in the area lobbed tear gas canisters to disperse the mob. About 14 persons were injured.
A clash erupted between cadres of United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF) and Nepali Congress (NC) during the NC municipal convention in Rajbiraj of Saptari district on Monday.

Earlier on Sunday, at least eight people including four police personnel were injured when a clash was ensued between UDMF and police at Bharmapuri as the latter barred a group of UDMF cadres who tried to gherao NC leader Lila Koirala's house.

A violent clash erupted between the Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha (UDMF) activists and the security personnel in Janakpur on Sunday, after the protesters hurled Molotov cocktail targeting the house of Nepali Congress (NC) lawmaker Leela Koirala. Around 10 people were injured in the incident.

Cadres of agitating Madhesi parties on Sunday foiled local conventions of Nepali Congress party in Janakpurdham. As they staged demonstrations with an aim to obstruct the convention in Janakpur Sub-Metropolitan City-4, police resorted to lobbing tear gas shells to disperse the protesters. Consequently, a clash ensued between the Madhesi parties' cadres and police in front of NC lawmaker Lila Koirala's house. UDMF

Meanwhile, a clash ensued between the police personnel and the cadres of Madhes-based parties near the statue of martyr Tej Bahadur Amatya. It has been learnt that as many as one dozen demonstrators were injured in the clash.

Police personnel were attacked with khukuri during the Nepali Congress ward committee election in Dharan of Sunsari today. Police head constable Jit Bahadur Baraili and constable Suraj Kumar Sah were injured when two youths, who had recently joined the party attacked them at the voting centre in a community forest in Dharan-19.
Nepali Congress Municipal Committee, Parsa, took out a motorcycle rally on the occasion of Martyrs' Day.
Morcha cadres gathered again on Friday at the Miteri bridge and burnt tyres in protest after the news of obstruction being lifted came to light.

Local conventions in one mountain and five Tarai districts could not take place on Friday due to protests of the Madhes-based political parties and the NC's internal dispute at the local level. The party could not hold local conventions in Bara, Parsa, Dhanusha, Siraha, Solukhumbu districts and three constituencies of Sarlahi.

The imports and exports had been disrupted since yesterday afternoon following the demonstration by the Hindu devotees known as Kanwariyas at Sirsiya Chowk.
Regular health services at Manipal College were disrupted today after the hospital employees took to the streets demanding pay hike.

Activists of the Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha on Monday continued their protests at the Birgunj-Raxaul customs point, obstructing movement of vehicles. After the constitution was amended on Saturday, it was expected that protesters would retreat from the border area.

Activists of Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha and Sanghiya Samabesi Madhesi Gathabandhan burnt the copies of amendments and staged demonstration at Jana-Aandolan Chok in the district. Two separate alliances of the agitating Madhes-centric parties burnt copies of constitution amendment at Rajbiraj, Saptari on Sunday, saying that the constitution amended on Saturday does not addresses the concerns raised by the agitating Madhes-based parties.
UDMF cadres and agitators staged rallies in Morang's Katahari, Naya Bazaar, Rangeli and Dainia areas from early morning.

UDMF cadres and agitators staged rallies in Morang's Katahari, Naya Bazaar, Rangeli and Dainia areas from early morning. They disrupted vehicular movement and closed market places in Dainia and Rangeli.

Agitators staged a rally near Rautahat DAO in Gaur from early morning. They burned tyres, enforced closure of transport services and closed market places in protest against the killing of 3 protesters the day before. The UDMF cadres also pelted stones at CPN-UML senior leader Madhav Kumar Nepal's house in Gaur.
UDMF cadres and agitators staged rallies in Morang's Katahari, Naya Bazaar, Rangeli and Dainia areas from early morning.

UDMF cadres and agitators staged rallies in Morang's Katahari, Naya Bazaar, Rangeli and Dainia areas from early morning. They disrupted vehicular movement and closed market places in Dainia and Rangeli. UDMF cadres vandalised two motorbikes in Rangeli bazaar. They also vandalised an under construction APF Border Security Post at Chopraha, Rangeli Municipality-3. Morang SP Tarini Prasad Lamsal said a large number of security personnel had been mobilised to maintain security in the district.

A demonstration staged by cadres of the United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF), protesting the death of three killed in Rangeli firing on Friday has disturbed the normal life in Birgunj. Meanwhile, a clash erupted between the cadres and the security personnel near Ghantaghar following their protests.
On 22 January, UDMF cadres threw a petrol bomb at Janaki Police Post in Janakpur.

In protest against the killing of 3 persons in police firing the day before in Rangeli and Dainiya in Morang, UDMF supporters also closed Inaruwa, the district headquarters of Sunsari, for an hour. Inaruwa and Duhabi in the district have got tense after the Rangeli incident.

Tensions escalated in Janakpur since early on Friday after supporters of the UDMF and the Sanghiya Samabesi Madhesi Gathabandhan started their demonstration by burning tyres in various parts of the district.
Riots erupted in Lahan of Siraha where the East West Highway was blocked. The Land Revenue office was vandalised and its chief Gyanraj Lamsal manhandled.
Speaking in a protest assembly organised at Musaharniya in Saptari district on Friday, Sadbhawana Party Chairman Mahato hinted at yesterday's Rangeli incident.
In Saptari, the enraged UDMF protesters shut schools and colleges.

source: Kathmandu Post; My Republica (Nepal); Himalayan Times
notes: Two persons have died and five others injured in police firing at Rangeli Bazaar in Morang district. Tensions flared up in the city after Morcha cadres attempted to disrupt a programme organised by CPN-UML youth wing Youth Association of Nepal (YAN). Later reports refer to 3 killed in Rangeli and nearby Dainiya area together.

UDMF activists also staged demonstrations in the area on Wednesday evening. They clashed with police as the latter resorted to baton charge. The UDMF said some of its activists sustained injuries in the incident. Morcha protesters took to the street since early morning and enforced a banda. They burnt tyres at major junctions in the bazaar area and also obstructed vehicular movement.
Front's cadres have gathered at major crossings of the city burning tires in Birganj. The marketplaces and transportation here which opened some one week ago have been shuttered yet again on Tuesday.
On Monday evening, the UDMF took out a torch rally in Birganj.

assoc_actor_1: UDMF: United Democratic Madhes Front; Labour Group (Nepal)
notes: Workers expressed solidarity with the ongoing Madhes agitation and organised a mass demonstration called by the United Democratic Madhesi Front with the initiative of Madhesi Trade Union Federation Nepal Parsa in Birgunj on Sunday.

Agitating Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha has taken out a lathi rally in various Tarai districts on Saturday as per their pre-announced protest programmes. Rallies were organised in Sarlahi, Bara, Janakpur, among others Tarai districts.

Cadres of United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF) disrupted a function organized by the 'new force' (Naya Shakti Nepal) led by former Prime Minister Baburam Bhattarai in Lahan on Monday. There was a scuffle between UDMF cadres and new force supporters. During the scuffle, UDMF cadres manhandled some supporters of the new force including Ramrijhan Yadav. After police's intervention, clashes among the supporters of UDMF, new force and police followed.

Women Security Pressure Group Nepal held a protest rally at Maitighar Mandla in Kathmandu on Sunday, demanding that the government control black marketeering and secure the human rights of its citizens.

A sit-in was held at the party office by leaders and cadres of the districts that are shrouded in controversy over active membership and whether or not to grant voting rights to new members, while the NC central members held their meeting in the party office building in Sanepa, Lalitpur.
The UDMF held a demonstration in the Janaki Chowk area in the evening. After the arson earlier, the protesters padlocked shops of four businessmen in the evening calling them 'anti-Madhes'.
A group of demonstrators vandalised three dozen tempos at Sankharachayra gate for defying the banda (bandh).
The Sanghiya Samabesi Madhesi Gathbandhan took out a baton rally in the morning.

assoc_actor_1: Labour Group (Nepal); CPN(UML): Communist Party of Nepal (Unified Marxist-Leninist); NC: Nepali Congress
notes: During a demonstration, local businessmen of Janakpur on Thursday torched motorcycles of Samyukta Loktantrik Madhesi Morcha (UDMF) aligned district leaders. The UDMF leaders have accused that the arson was carried out by CPN-UML and Nepali Congress cadres infiltrated into the group of businessmen.

Clashes erupted between local businessmen and cadres of the United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF) at Janaki Chowk here on Thursday. UDMF leaders accuse Nepali Congress and UML of intervening in the rally. Two motorcycles were set on fire during the clashes.

assoc_actor_1: NNTA: Nepal National Teachers Association; Teachers (Nepal)
notes: The teachers organisations' representatives padlocked the office of District Education Officer Ganesh Bahadur Singh today. Teachers' organisations in Kailali have launched an agitation against the District Education Officer, accusing him of acting against past agreements and understandings.

On 6 Jan, a group of porters clashed with the cadres of Sanghiya Samabeshi Madhesi Gathabandhan (SSMG) at Miteri bridge near Birgunj-Raxaul border (Birganj, Parsa). Three people sustained injuries. The clash erupted when the SSMG cadres tried to obstruct the porters from crossing the bridge.

Indian nationals have attacked Madhesi cadres staging a sit-in at Birgunj check-point on Wednesday morning. According to SP Raju Babu Shrestha a group of around 20-25 Indian citizens, mostly Raxual-based local businessmen, clashed with the UDMF cadres after a verbal exchange with them.

An unidentified group hurled a petrol bomb at the Kathmandu-based office of GMR -- an Indian company developing Upper Karnali (900 MW) and Upper Marshyangdi (600 MW) hydropower projects -- on Tuesday evening.

A police official was fatally shot at by an armed group at Jhauraha Chok of Nargho VDC of Saptari district on Monday evening. Two motorcycle-borne assailants had opened fire at ASI Ramesh Subba, the in-charge of Jhutaki police post, in the neighbouring village. Akhil Tarai Mukti Morcha, an underground armed outfit, led by Jayakrishna Goit has taken up the responsibility of the attack.

assoc_actor_1: HURPES: Human Rights and Peace Society
notes: Police have rounded up 35 HURPES activists who were staging a sit-in at Indian Embassy in Lainchaur, Kathmandu on Friday. The protest programme was called by Human Rights and Peace Society of Nepal against India's unofficial blockade and government's apathy to address the crisis.

There were around a hundred protesters at the Birgunj-Raxaul border on Friday afternoon, amongst others two members--Laxmanlal Karn and Lalbabu Raut Gaddi--of the talks team from the United Democratic Madhesi Front (UDMF).
